cal activists and practitioners of ayurveda, India's largest indigenous medical system, have been able to undermine the aspirations of multinational companies and the WTO. Halliburton traces how key drug prices have gone down, not up, in low-income countries under the new patent regime through partnerships between US- and India-based companies, but warns us to be aware of access to essential medicines in low- and middle-income countries going forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aDrugszIndiaxPatents. 0aIntellectual propertyzIndia. 0aMedicine, AyurvedicxEconomic aspectszIndia. 0aPatent laws and legislationzIndia. 0aPatents (International law) 0aPharmaceutical industryzIndia. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106658710 cprintz978150171346040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501713972?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501713972zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501713972/original  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066587-1 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA